\fs28 \cf4 \cb3 By Iain Poulson\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 Key points:
\f1\b0 \cb1 \
\cb3 For years, WordPress theme settings were scattered \'96 defined in
\f3\i  functions.php
\f1\i0 , buried in PHP hooks, or hardcoded into stylesheets. It worked, but barely. Now, there\'92s 
\f3\i theme.json
\f1\i0  \'96 a single, declarative file that brings order to the chaos. It centralizes theme configuration and design tokens, letting developers define global settings like colors, typography, layout, and spacing in one place.\cb1 \
\cb3 The real payoff is in the block editor: 
\f3\i theme.json
\f1\i0  powers the Global Styles interface, so designers can tweak visual styles directly \'96 without risking layout breakage. Developers, meanwhile, keep control over what can and can\'92t be changed. The output is lean: only the CSS you specify, with no bloat and fewer fights over selector priority.\cb1 \
\cb3 More than just a convenience, 
\f3\i theme.json
\f1\i0  is now the standard foundation of all core themes. It\'92s tightly integrated with the WordPress editor and aligned with where the platform is headed.\cb1 \
\cb3 Let\'92s explore how it works and why it\'92s fundamental for modern WordPress development.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa398\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs48 \cf2 \cb3 What is theme.json in WordPress?\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 In WordPress, 
\f3\i theme.json
\f1\i0  is a single configuration file placed at the root of a theme. It defines global settings and styles for both the block editor and the front end using a structured JSON format.\cb1 \
\cb3 This file brings consistency and predictability to theme development by centralizing what used to be scattered across 
\f3\i functions.php
\f1\i0 , 
\f4\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cb5 add_theme_support()
\f1\fs32 \cb3  calls, and custom stylesheets.\cb1 \
\cb3 Using JSON makes configurations easier for WordPress to parse and for developers and teams to share. It\'92s the same reason {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.advancedcustomfields.com/resources/acf-block-configuration-via-block-json/"}}{\fldrslt \cb3 \ul we use it to configure ACF Blocks}}.\cb1 \
\cb3 It works in both classic and block themes; it\'92s technically optional, but almost every modern theme includes it as a standard practice.\cb1 \
\cb3 This file powers the Global Styles interface in the editor, giving users a visual way to customize colors, typography, layout, and spacing without needing to write code.\cb1 \
\cb3 Behind the scenes, it serves as the single source of truth for theme design, feeding four layers of style data \'96 core defaults, block defaults, theme values, and user customizations \'96 which WordPress merges at runtime.\cb1 \
\cb3 One of its biggest benefits is reducing the need for excessive {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://wpengine.com/resources/customize-theme-css/"}}{\fldrslt \cb3 \ul custom CSS}}. Only the necessary styles are generated, in the correct cascade order, helping to avoid conflicts and unnecessary overrides.\cb1 \
\cb3 Beyond styles, 
\f3\i theme.json
\f1\i0  is also extensible: you can define templates, template parts, patterns, and block style variations under structured keys.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa398\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs48 \cf2 \cb3 Understanding the structure of theme.json\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 Here\'92s a breakdown of the main components you\'92ll define in a 
\f3\i theme.json
\f1\i0  file \'96 and what each one controls.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa400\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs40 \cf2 \cb3 Schema\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 The 
\f4\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cb5 $schema
\f1\fs32 \cb3  key is an optional but recommended top-level entry in theme.json. It links to the official WordPress JSON Schema \'96 typically something like 
\f4\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cb5 "$schema": "https://schemas.wp.org/trunk/theme.json"
\f1\fs32 \cb3 \'a0 \'96 or a version-specific path such as 
\f3\i /wp/6.5/theme.json
\f1\i0 .\cb1 \
\cb3 Adding this enables advanced features in modern code editors and IDEs, including autocompletion, real-time validation, and inline documentation for available keys and values.\cb1 \
\cb3 It has zero effect on how WordPress renders the theme; it exists purely to improve the developer experience. Some schema validators require it to be listed before the version key, so placing it at the top is best practice.\cb1 \
\cb3 While WordPress functions fine without it, skipping it means you\'92ll lose helpful editor features that can prevent syntax errors and speed up configuration.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa400\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs40 \cf2 \cb3 Version\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 The 
\f4\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cb5 version
\f1\fs32 \cb3  key is a required top-level field in theme.json that tells WordPress which version of the spec your theme uses:\cb1 \
\cb3 Each version expands what the theme can configure. If WordPress doesn\'92t recognize the version number, it quietly falls back to version 1 behavior. That means no errors, but also no access to newer features. To prevent this, only update the version key when your theme\'92s minimum WordPress requirement matches the version of the spec you\'92re targeting.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa400\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs40 \cf2 \cb3 Settings\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 The 
\f4\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cb5 settings
\f1\fs32 \cb3  object is the core of theme.json, defining what users can customize in the block editor and setting the design system for your theme. This is where you enable or disable editor features and register design tokens like colors, fonts, spacing, and more.\cb1 \
\cb3 Settings follow a hierarchy:\cb1 \
\cb3 Common setting groups include color, typography, spacing, layout, border, dimensions, appearanceTools, and custom.\cb1 \
\cb3 These settings populate the Global Styles UI, giving users predefined options while preventing option overload. You control what can be changed and what stays locked, reducing inconsistencies across a site.\cb1 \
\cb3 Here\'92s an example of what you might find in this segment:\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f4\fs20\fsmilli10240 \cf6 \cb7 "settings": \{\
  "color": \{\
    "palette": [\
    \{ "slug": "brand", "color": "#0057ff", "name": "Brand Blue" \}\
    ]\
  \},\
  "typography": \{\
    "fontFamilies": [\
    \{ "slug": "inter", "fontFamily": "Inter, sans-serif", "name": "Inter" \}\
    ]\
  \}\
\}
\fs25\fsmilli12800 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 This code registers a custom color and font, which then appear in the editor\'92s design tools and are used throughout the site.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa400\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs40 \cf2 \cb3 Custom templates\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 The customTemplates key lets you register additional page templates that appear in the Template dropdown within the editor. These are useful for offering alternate layouts \'96 like a no-header landing page \'96 without requiring users to touch code.\cb1 \
\cb3 Each template entry is an object with three fields:\cb1 \
\cb3 Take the code sample below:\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f4\fs20\fsmilli10240 \cf6 \cb7 "customTemplates": [\
  \{\
    "name": "landing-no-header",\
    "title": "Landing \'96 No Header",\
    "postTypes": ["page"]\
  \}\
]
\fs25\fsmilli12800 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 Once registered, this template appears in the Template selector for the defined post types, allowing authors to apply a custom layout without modifying code. It works in both block and classic themes, as long as the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.advancedcustomfields.com/blog/wordpress-file-structure/"}}{\fldrslt \cb3 \ul file structure}} matches the name.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa400\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs40 \cf2 \cb3 Template parts\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 The 
\f4\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cb5 templateParts
\f1\fs32 \cb3  key registers reusable layout sections \'96 like headers, footers, or sidebars \'96 for use in the Site Editor. These parts live in the parts/ directory of your theme and are referenced by name.\cb1 \
\cb3 Each entry includes:\cb1 \
\cb3 Here\'92s an example:\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f4\fs20\fsmilli10240 \cf6 \cb7 "templateParts": [\
  \{\
    "name": "header",\
    "title": "Site Header",\
    "area": "header"\
  \}\
]
\fs25\fsmilli12800 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 Registering parts this way exposes them in the Site Editor\'92s \'93Replace\'94 panel, making it easier to swap in alternate versions. It also enables translation of part titles and clarifies their purpose for both users and developers.\cb1 \
\cb3 These parts can then be referenced in full-page templates using block markup like 
\f4\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cb5 <!-- wp:template-part \{"slug":"header"\} /-->
\f1\fs32 \cb3 .\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa400\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs40 \cf2 \cb3 Patterns\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 The 
\f4\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cb5 patterns
\f1\fs32 \cb3  key allows you to bundle {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.advancedcustomfields.com/blog/wordpress-reusable-block/"}}{\fldrslt \cb3 \ul pre-designed block patterns}} with your theme by referencing their slugs. These can come from the official WordPress Pattern Directory or be registered by plugins, e.g.:\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f4\fs20\fsmilli10240 \cf6 \cb7 "patterns": [\
  "two-column-cta",\
  "pricing-table-staggered"\
]
\fs25\fsmilli12800 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 This setup ensures those patterns are readily available in the editor, giving users curated starting points for building pages while keeping your {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://wpengine.com/builders/block-theme-templates/"}}{\fldrslt \cb3 \ul block theme templates}} neat and flexible.\cb1 \
\cb3 When the theme is activated, WordPress fetches the specified patterns so they appear in the Block Inserter under the Patterns tab.\cb1 \
\cb3 This is a lightweight way to provide layout ideas or reusable design sections without hardcoding them into templates. You can also combine bundled patterns with synced (formerly reusable) patterns created in the Site Editor, letting users update all instances of a pattern site-wide from one place.\cb1 \
\cb3 There are two ways to modify 
\f3\i theme.json
\f1\i0 : by editing the file directly or by using the Full Site Editor (FSE) to adjust styles visually.\cb1 \
\cb3 For simple changes like updating colors or fonts, the FSE is often safer and faster, especially for non-developers \'96 it reduces the risk of breaking anything with a syntax error.\cb1 \
\cb3 For site owners or editors, the FSE is perfect for rebranding, quick visual fixes, or updates to a live site without needing server access.\cb1 \
\cb3 Developers, on the other hand, may use the FSE to prototype styles, then export those settings to commit into code.\cb1 \
\cb3 Editing the file directly also allows for advanced configuration, like adding new palette values or using keys not exposed in the UI, and ensures the design system stays version-controlled and portable.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa400\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs40 \cf2 \cb3 Method 1. Making customizations via the Site Editor\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

