\f2\b\fs40 \cf2 \cb3 Method 2. Advanced customizations with code\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 There\'92s a lot you can do with 
\f3\i theme.json
\f1\i0  via the Site Editor, meaning you only need to edit it for more advanced settings. Or when you\'92re {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.advancedcustomfields.com/blog/wordpress-custom-theme-development/"}}{\fldrslt \cb3 \ul building a theme from scratch}}, of course.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Batch editing
\f1\b0  is one example of an advanced use case, where editing the file directly is more practical. Some of the things you can do here include:\cb1 \
\cb3 1. Creating a global link style, where one rule touches every hyperlink in every block:\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f4\fs20\fsmilli10240 \cf6 \cb7 "styles": \{\
  "elements": \{\
    "link": \{ "color": \{ "text": "var(--wp--preset--color--brand)" \} \}\
  \}\
\}
\fs25\fsmilli12800 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 2. Setting a uniform block gap site\uc0\u8209 wide. Set it once, and it cascades everywhere instead of tweaking dozens of templates:\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f4\fs20\fsmilli10240 \cf6 \cb7 "styles": \{ "spacing": \{ "blockGap": "1.5rem" \} \}
\fs25\fsmilli12800 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 Performance optimization is another area where the Site Editor just can\'92t cut it. You can:\cb1 \
\cb3 3. Restrict color and spacing tools so WordPress ships a lighter stylesheet:\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f4\fs20\fsmilli10240 \cf6 \cb7 "settings": \{\
  "color":  \{ "custom": false \},\
  "spacing":\{ "units": ["rem","px"], "padding": false \}\
\}
\fs25\fsmilli12800 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 4. Predetermine content widths to avoid oversizing images and keep layout calculations fast:\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f4\fs20\fsmilli10240 \cf6 \cb7 "settings": \{ "layout": \{ "contentSize": "720px", "wideSize": "1200px" \} \}
\fs25\fsmilli12800 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 5. Toggle fluid typography to generate a single 
\f4\fs25\fsmilli12800 \cb5 clamp()
\f1\fs32 \cb3  rule per size instead of multiple media queries:\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f4\fs20\fsmilli10240 \cf6 \cb7 "settings": \{ "typography": \{ "fluid": true \} \}
\fs25\fsmilli12800 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa398\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs48 \cf2 \cb3 Using ACF Blocks with theme.json\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 As we stated in an earlier section, we love JSON because it provides a much easier and readable way to structure data.\cb1 \
\cb3 When {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.advancedcustomfields.com/resources/create-your-first-acf-block/"}}{\fldrslt \cb3 \ul creating a custom ACF Block}}, you\'92ll configure it using a 
\f3\i block.json
\f1\i0  file. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.advancedcustomfields.com/blog/wordpress-development-best-practices/"}}{\fldrslt \cb3 \ul To speed up development}}, you can inherit styles from 
\f3\i theme.json
\f1\i0  by adding the following code to 
\f3\i block.json
\f1\i0 :\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f4\fs20\fsmilli10240 \cf6 \cb7 "supports": \{\
  "color": true,\
  "spacing": true,\
  "typography": true\
\}
\fs25\fsmilli12800 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb3 This will result in a sidebar that shows your theme\'92s color palette, spacing scale, and fonts for you to pick when editing your custom block in Gutenberg. It\'92s a faster, more scalable method for displaying custom field data on the frontend.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa398\partightenfactor0

